From: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
Subject: [PATCH] nss_core: back firmware empty-buffer payloads with kmalloc

The empty-buffer pool skbs are handed to the NSS firmware, which keeps
them in custody indefinitely (n2h_empty_pool_buf + n2h_wifi_pool_buf,
~14.5k skbs on a two-radio IPQ8074 with the wifili pool configured).
dev_alloc_skb() carves their ~2KB payloads out of the shared per-CPU
page-frag caches, i.e. 32KB compound chunks holding up to 13 buffers,
interleaved with short-lived traffic skbs. Every payload the firmware
keeps pins its entire chunk once the neighbouring buffers are freed,
and the pool slowly diffuses across chunks as buffers cycle through
the firmware.

Measured on a 512MB AX3600 after 5h of uptime (full-pfn page census):
6098 order-3 frag chunks = 195MB pinned, holding ~14.4k custody
payloads = ~34MB of actual buffer memory - a ~5x amplification that
plateaus only when most custody buffers sit in near-empty chunks. A
100s saturation burst diluted the pool further (+334 chunks for +135
payloads) and idle time does not recover the memory.

Allocate the pool payloads with alloc_skb() instead: each payload gets
its own kmalloc object (kmalloc-4096 for the default 1792-byte medium
profile buffer), freed in full the moment the skb is freed, bounding
pool memory at one page per buffer with zero cross-lifetime pinning.
The skb geometry is unchanged (same payload_len mapping, NET_SKB_PAD
headroom restored via skb_reserve; the firmware reports payload_offs
relative to head on return, and tailroom only grows). Allocation cost
moves from page-frag carve to slab alloc on the refill path only,
which runs at pool-churn rate, not per-packet rate.

Signed-off-by: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
--- a/nss_core.c
+++ b/nss_core.c
@@ -2033,7 +2033,18 @@ static void nss_core_alloc_max_avail_siz
 		dma_addr_t buffer;
 		struct h2n_descriptor *desc = &desc_ring[hlos_index];
 
-		struct sk_buff *nbuf = dev_alloc_skb(max_buf_size);
+		/*
+		 * These skbs are handed to the NSS firmware, which keeps
+		 * them in its empty-buffer pool indefinitely. They must not
+		 * come from the shared per-CPU page-frag caches
+		 * (dev_alloc_skb): a long-held ~2KB payload pins its whole
+		 * 32KB frag chunk once the neighbouring traffic buffers are
+		 * freed, which measured as ~5x RAM amplification on a 512MB
+		 * IPQ8074 (~200MB pinned for ~35MB of payloads). alloc_skb()
+		 * backs each payload with its own kmalloc object instead,
+		 * which is returned in full the moment the skb is freed.
+		 */
+		struct sk_buff *nbuf = alloc_skb(payload_len, GFP_ATOMIC);
 		if (unlikely(!nbuf)) {
 			/*
 			 * ERR:
@@ -2042,6 +2053,7 @@ static void nss_core_alloc_max_avail_siz
 			nss_warning("%px: Could not obtain empty buffer", nss_ctx);
 			break;
 		}
+		skb_reserve(nbuf, NET_SKB_PAD);
 
 		/*
 		 * Map the skb
